Rules:
Rule 1: Preserve one shared backend. All behavior changes must be implemented in shared core modules, then surfaced through interfaces (CLI, GUI, scripts/notebooks).
Rule 2: Do not create separate logic paths per interface for constitutional processing. CLI, GUI, and scripts must all call `run_constitutional_turn`.
Rule 3: Reuse library functions and datamodels instead of reimplementing request, config, or transcript behavior.
Rule 4: When uncertain about behavior, inspect current signatures and ask for clarification before inventing APIs.
Rule 5: Respect runtime configuration (`RuntimeSettings`, prompts, rules) and avoid hardcoding values in generated code.
Rule 6: Prefer minimal working examples that import from `constitutional_ai.*`.
Rule 7: Do not expose API keys in logs, responses, or generated examples.
Rule 8: Keep `README.md` and `README.llm` aligned when adding engine features, CLI commands, or server endpoints.
Rule 9: After each code edit, update `README.md` and `README.llm` to reflect the latest repository behavior.
Rule 10: All code must include documentation: module/function/class docstrings, plus concise comments for non-obvious logic.

<ReadMe.LLM>

<library_description>
This repository provides a Constitutional AI package with one shared engine and multiple interfaces.

Purpose:
- run writer/judge constitutional loops over user prompts
- support sequential and parallel rule-evaluation modes
- expose the same core behavior through CLI, GUI server, and Python imports

Main components:
- `constitutional_ai.engine`: core constitutional loop (`run_constitutional_turn`)
- `constitutional_ai.config`: load/merge/save config and runtime settings
- `constitutional_ai.client`: shared OpenAI chat-completions request layer
- `constitutional_ai.models`: typed dataclasses for messages and transcripts
- `constitutional_ai.cli`: command-line interface
- `constitutional_ai.server`: GUI + HTTP API wrapper around shared engine

Key architecture constraint:
- there is one backend core. Interfaces must only adapt input/output and call shared modules.
</library_description>

<context_1>
<context_1_description>
Core engine entrypoint for one constitutional reasoning turn.
All interfaces should call this function rather than duplicating logic.
</context_1_description>

<context_1_function>
run_constitutional_turn(
    *,
    user_text: str,
    thread_messages: list[ChatMessage],
    config: AppConfig
) -> TurnTranscript
</context_1_function>

<context_1_notes>
- Generates an initial writer draft.
- Evaluates rules via judge.
- Sequential mode: evaluates rules one-by-one with per-rule revisions.
- Parallel mode: evaluates all rules in parallel, critiques failing rules in parallel, performs one combined revision per round.
- Returns structured transcript (`writer.drafts`, `judge.checks`, `usage`, `final`).
</context_1_notes>

<context_1_example>
from constitutional_ai.config import load_config
from constitutional_ai.engine import run_constitutional_turn
from constitutional_ai.models import ChatMessage

config = load_config()
thread = [ChatMessage(role="user", content="Explain constitutional AI in 3 bullets.")]

turn = run_constitutional_turn(
    user_text=thread[-1].content,
    thread_messages=thread,
    config=config,
)

print(turn.final)
</context_1_example>
</context_1>

<context_2>
<context_2_description>
Configuration loading and persistence. Used by CLI, GUI server, and scripts.
</context_2_description>

<context_2_function>
load_config(path: str | Path | None = None) -> AppConfig
</context_2_function>

<context_2_related_functions>
save_config(config: AppConfig, path: str | Path | None = None) -> Path
merge_config(base: AppConfig, payload: dict[str, Any] | None) -> AppConfig
normalize_base_url(value: str) -> str
</context_2_related_functions>

<context_2_notes>
- Config default path: `~/.constitutional_ai/config.json`.
- `OPENAI_API_KEY` environment variable overrides stored API key at load time.
- `base_url` is normalized/validated to prevent malformed OpenAI endpoint construction.
- Runtime settings include execution mode and parallel iteration limit.
</context_2_notes>

<context_2_example>
from constitutional_ai.config import load_config, merge_config

base = load_config()
cfg = merge_config(
    base,
    {
        "settings": {
            "execution_mode": "parallel",
            "parallel_max_iterations": 1,
        }
    },
)
</context_2_example>
</context_2>

<context_3>
<context_3_description>
Primary message model used for thread history.
</context_3_description>

<context_3_function>
ChatMessage(
    role: Literal["user", "assistant"],
    content: str,
    at: str = now_iso()
)
</context_3_function>

<context_3_notes>
- Use `ChatMessage` for thread inputs to `run_constitutional_turn`.
- Convert to OpenAI message format via `to_openai()` internally.
- Validate untrusted mappings with `ChatMessage.from_mapping`.
</context_3_notes>

<context_3_example>
from constitutional_ai.models import ChatMessage

history = [
    ChatMessage(role="user", content="Hello"),
    ChatMessage(role="assistant", content="Hi, how can I help?"),
]
</context_3_example>
</context_3>

<context_4>
<context_4_description>
CLI interface for single-turn and interactive use. It is a thin wrapper around shared config + shared engine.
</context_4_description>

<context_4_function>
constitutional-ai run --prompt "<text>" [--config PATH] [--rules-file PATH]
                      [--api-key KEY] [--writer-model MODEL] [--judge-model MODEL]
                      [--execution-mode sequential|parallel]
                      [--parallel-max-iterations N] [--json]

constitutional-ai chat [--config PATH]
                       [--execution-mode sequential|parallel]
                       [--parallel-max-iterations N]
</context_4_function>

<context_4_notes>
- `run` executes one turn and prints final answer (or transcript JSON with `--json`).
- `chat` maintains local conversation history and calls shared engine each turn.
- Avoid adding interface-specific backend logic here; keep processing in engine/client.
</context_4_notes>

<context_4_example>
# Single turn
constitutional-ai run --prompt "Summarize constitutional AI"

# Parallel mode with one rewrite round
constitutional-ai run --prompt "Draft policy guidance" \
  --execution-mode parallel \
  --parallel-max-iterations 1
</context_4_example>
</context_4>

<context_5>
<context_5_description>
GUI server and HTTP endpoints. The server exposes static GUI assets and API routes, but still uses the same core engine.
</context_5_description>

<context_5_function>
Server entrypoint:
constitutional-ai-gui [--host 127.0.0.1] [--port 8765] [--config PATH] [--no-open]

HTTP endpoints:
GET  /api/config
POST /api/config
POST /api/turn
</context_5_function>

<context_5_notes>
- `GET /api/config`: returns current config + metadata (API key source, first-run state), with API key redacted.
- `POST /api/config`: merges and persists config updates.
- `POST /api/turn`: runs one constitutional turn via `run_constitutional_turn`.
- Additional utility endpoint exists: `POST /api/test-connection` for settings connectivity checks.
- First run auto-creates starter config if missing and supports GUI-only setup.
</context_5_notes>

<context_5_example>
curl -s http://127.0.0.1:8765/api/config

curl -s -X POST http://127.0.0.1:8765/api/turn \
  -H "Content-Type: application/json" \
  -d '{
    "user_text": "Explain constitutional AI",
    "thread_messages": [{"role":"user","content":"Explain constitutional AI"}]
  }'
</context_5_example>
</context_5>

<context_6>
<context_6_description>
Shared request client to OpenAI chat-completions. This is the only request builder used by engine and server checks.
</context_6_description>

<context_6_function>
chat_completion(
    *,
    api_key: str,
    base_url: str,
    model: str,
    messages: list[dict[str, str]],
    temperature: float,
    max_tokens: int,
    timeout_ms: int
) -> CompletionResult
</context_6_function>

<context_6_notes>
- Final endpoint URL is built centrally from normalized base URL.
- Debug URL logging can be enabled with `CONSTITUTIONAL_AI_DEBUG=1`.
- Never log API keys.
</context_6_notes>

<context_6_example>
from constitutional_ai.client import chat_completion

res = chat_completion(
    api_key="...",
    base_url="https://api.openai.com",
    model="gpt-4o-mini",
    messages=[{"role": "user", "content": "Reply with OK"}],
    temperature=0.0,
    max_tokens=8,
    timeout_ms=45000,
)
print(res.content)
</context_6_example>
</context_6>

<maintenance_policy>
When adding or changing any of the following, update BOTH `README.md` and `README.llm` in the same change:
- engine behavior or signatures
- config fields/defaults/validation
- CLI commands/options
- GUI server endpoints or first-run flow
- data models used in public examples

Documentation standard for all ongoing changes:
- Include module docstrings in Python files.
- Include function/class docstrings in Python.
- Include concise inline comments where logic is non-trivial.
- Keep JavaScript function-level doc comments up to date.
</maintenance_policy>

<agent_prompt_template>
Use this template when prompting an LLM/coding agent to modify this repo:

1) Read and follow `README.llm`.
2) Preserve one backend core (`engine.py` + shared client/config); do not fork logic across CLI/GUI/scripts.
3) Implement requested changes in shared modules first, then wire interfaces.
4) Update `README.md` and `README.llm` if public behavior changes.
5) Provide validation steps and list affected files.
</agent_prompt_template>

</ReadMe.LLM>
